ide in oil prices, analysts said as the energy futures marketgyrated widly.   Oil futures veered lower Wednesday as trading opened, but bylate afternoon had recovered the day's lost ground and rose aboveTuesday's close. Oil prices have fallen about 25 percent sinceJanuary.</TEXT><DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   OPEC nations have held ``intensediscussions'' about the recent sharp fall in oil prices, with someministers considering whether to call an emergency meeting,analysts said.   ``There has been some contact among the ministers about thepossibility of meeting to discuss the problem,'' a source close tothe Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, who demandedanonymity, said Wednesday.   OPEC spokesmen in Vienna, the group's headquarters, said nomeeting had been planned.</TEXT><DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Shell Oil Co. unveiled its own version of areformulated gasoline that reduces certain exhaust pollutants andsaid the gas will be sold in nine U.S. metropolitan areas where airquality is a problem.   The SU 2000E gasoline reduces hydrocarbon vapor emissions, acomponent in smog formation, and carbon monoxide emissions fromautomobile tailpipes, Shell officials said Wednesday.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Standard andamp; Poor's Corp. is taking a closer lookat its ratings on about $7.1 billion in long-term public debt andpreferred stock of Time Warner Inc. because of the media andentertainment giant's new financial agreement with PatheCommunications Corp.   Standard andamp; Poor's, one of the nation's leading credit ratingservices, said it was placing $1.5 billion in Time Warner debt and$5.6 billion of its preferred stock on its CreditWatch listing withnegative implications.   The move is not an actual credit downgrade, which if undertakenwould increase Time Warner's borrowing costs.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The student loan default rate has dippedslightly and Education Department officials said they will studythe statistics to see if a trend may be emerging.   Officials said Wednesday that the department data show anoverall default rate reduction from 17.3 percent in 1987 to 15.6percent in fiscal year 1988. In fiscal year 1986, the default ratewas 21 percent.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   One in eight Americans has no healthinsurance, the Census Bureau reported.   A study concluded that 26.5 percent of Hispanic Americansweren't covered in 1988, while the figure was 20.2 percent forblacks and 11.7 percent for whites. The report Wednesday comes asthe Senate is considering a proposal to assure that all Americanshave private or public health coverage.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Energy issues posted broad losses Wednesday while the rest ofthe stock market drifted aimlessly in a quiet session. The DowJones industrial average slipped 1.35 to 2,729.73, marking thesixth consecutive session in which it rose or fell less than 10points.   The dollar ended narrowly mixed in thin trading.   Bond prices rose in response to a temporary drop in oil prices.   Orange juice futures prices leaped; livestock and meat futureswere mixed; grains and soybeans were mixed and precious metals weremixed.</TEXT></DOC>